05996nam a22009255i 9783110768275DE-B159720220524034747.0m|||||o||d||||||||cr || ||||||||220524t20222022gw     fo  d z      eng d  a2022932016  a97831107682757 a10.1515/97831107682752doi  a(DE-B1597)606742  aDE-B1597bengcDE-B1597erda0 aeng  agwcDE 7aHIS0220002bisacsh04a305.892404aThe Marrano Way :bBetween Betrayal and Innovation /ced. by Agata Bielik-Robson. 1aBerlin ;aBoston : bDe Gruyter, c[2022] 4c©2022  a1 online resource (VI, 372 p.)  atextbtxt2rdacontent  acomputerbc2rdamedia  aonline resourcebcr2rdacarrier  atext filebPDF2rda0 aPerspectives on Jewish Texts and Contexts ,x2199-6962 ;v190 arestricted accessuhttp://purl.org/coar/access_right/c_16ecfonline access with authorization2star  aThe Marrano phenomenon is a still unexplored element of Western culture: the presence of the borderline Jewish identity which avoids clear-cut cultural and religious attribution and – precisely as such – prefigures the advent of the typically modern "free-oscillating" subjectivity. Yet, the aim of the book is not a historical study of the Marranos (or conversos), who were forced to convert to Christianity, but were suspected of retaining their Judaism "undercover." The book rather applies the "Marrano metaphor" to explore the fruitful area of mixture and cross-over which allowed modern thinkers, writers and artists of the Jewish origin to enter the realm of universal communication – without, at the same time, making them relinquish their Jewishness which they subsequently developed as a "hidden tradition." The book poses and then attempts to prove the "Marrano hypothesis," according to which modern subjectivity derives, to paraphrase Cohen, "out of the sources of the hidden Judaism": modernity begins not with the Cartesian abstract ego, but with the rich self-reflexive self of Michel de Montaigne who wrestled with his own marranismo in a manner that soon became paradigmatic to other Jewish thinkers entering the scene of Western modernity, from Spinoza to Derrida. The essays in the volume offer thus a new view of a "Marrano modernity," which aims to radically transform our approach to the genesis of the modern subject and shed a new light on its secret religious life as surviving the process of secularization, although merely in the form of secret traces.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 24. Mai 2022) 7aHISTORY / Jewish.2bisacsh  aAssimilation.  aHidden Tradition.  aMarranism.  aModern Subjectivity.1 aBaert, Dennis, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aBielik-Robson, Agata, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aBielik-Robson, Agata, eeditor.4edt4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/edt1 aDolgopolski, Sergey, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aGaisin, Aleksandr, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aIdziak-Smoczyńska, Urszula, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aLapidot, Elad, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aLevy, Antoine, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aLipszyc, Adam, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aLiska, Vivian, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aPisano, Libera, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aRosenberg, Göran, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aSchwarz, Jan, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aSharvit, Gilad, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aTacik, Przemysław, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aWeiss, Daniel H., econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/rel